# Process hygiene (BigQuery emulator)

This repo spawns several classes of long-running, memory-hungry subprocess. The default agent failure mode is **leaving one or more of them alive** after a build, test, smoke, subagent run, or interruption. They then compound on the next invocation, eventually OOM'ing the box. The companion `.cursor/rules/bazel-process-hygiene.mdc` covers Bazel-specific posture; **this rule is broader and gates every session.**

## The catalog (what to look for)

These are the process names / patterns that this repo can leak. **Audit for every one** during the checks below. The catalog is the source of truth — if you add a new heavyweight subprocess to the repo, add it here.

| Class                       | Patterns to match (`ps -eo pid,etime,rss,args`)                                                                |
|----------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Bazel server + clients     | `bazel`, `bazelisk`, `process-wrapper`                                                                        |
| Compiler under Bazel       | `clang`, `clang++`, `cc1`, `cc1plus`, `gcc`, `g++` (the C++ link/compile can fork dozens)                     |
| BigQuery emulator engine   | `emulator_main` (the canonical `cc_binary`) and any test wrapper that exec'd it                                |
| BigQuery emulator gateway  | `gateway_main`, `bigquery-emulator-gateway` (Go binary spawned by tests / docker)                              |
| Conformance runner         | `conformance/cmd/runner`, `./runner`, any `runner_*.tmp.*` binary `go test` shelled out to                     |
| `go test` orchestrators    | `go-build`-cached test binaries under `/tmp/go-build*` that re-spawn the engine (look for `_test` suffix)      |
| Docker daemon-side build   | `buildkitd`, `containerd-shim`, BuildKit's `runc` children invoked for the `engine-builder` stage              |
| Docker image-side build    | Inside-the-container `bazel`/`clang` (visible via `docker stats` / `docker top <id>`, not host `ps`)            |

The `task bazel:status` helper greps for the Bazel/Clang subset and prints `(clean)` when nothing matches. **It does NOT cover the rest of the catalog** — use the full audit below for everything else.

## Pre-spawn audit (MANDATORY before any heavy command)

A "heavy command" is any of: `bazel ...`, `task bazel:*`, `task emulator:*`, `task conformance:run` against `bin/emulator_main`, `task docker:*`, `docker build`, `docker compose up --build`, `go test -tags=integration`, `./bin/emulator_main`, or invoking a subagent that may do any of the above.

Before spawning, run:

```bash
ps -eo pid,ppid,etime,pcpu,pmem,rss,args \
  | grep -E 'bazel|clang\b|cc1|process-wrapper|emulator_main|gateway_main|bigquery-emulator|conformance/cmd/runner|/runner |buildkitd|containerd-shim' \
  | grep -vE '\bgrep\b|/usr/bin/zsh' \
  || echo '(clean)'
```

If `(clean)`: proceed.

If anything is alive: decide between **wait**, **reuse**, or **kill the whole tree** (`task bazel:kill-strays` covers Bazel/clang; for the rest see "Cleanup" below). Do **not** spawn a parallel heavy command — even a fresh `docker build` while Bazel is running on the host will OOM a 32-GiB box because container Bazel and host Bazel both auto-detect the full host MemTotal.

Also snapshot host headroom:

```bash
free -h | head -2
```

If `available` is below `4 GiB`, the spawn will likely OOM. **Stop**, free memory first (see "Reclaim memory" below), and re-audit.

## Mid-loop poll (when a build / test exceeds 5 minutes)

A heavy command running > 5 minutes is normal for the C++ engine; the failure mode is a **silent fork bomb** (e.g. inside-container Bazel auto-detecting 14 jobs × 2 GiB/clang against the host's headroom-less RAM). On the next assistant turn while such a command is in flight, run:

```bash
free -h | head -2
ps -eo pcpu,pmem,rss,args --sort=-pmem | head -10
```

If any single process is over `4 GiB RSS` AND `free -h` `available` is dropping toward `2 GiB`, the build is about to OOM the box. **Kill the tree now** (host: `task bazel:kill-strays`; container: `docker kill <id>` for the `engine-builder` stage; runner: SIGTERM the runner PID and verify children also die). Do not assume the build will recover.

## Cleanup (MANDATORY after every heavy command, success OR failure)

End the heavy command's terminal turn with this block:

```bash
# 1. Bazel server + clients (covers bazelisk, clang under bazel, process-wrapper).
task bazel:shutdown
task bazel:kill-strays            # idempotent; only kills if anything is alive
task bazel:status                  # expect (clean)

# 2. Emulator + gateway processes spawned by tests, runners, smokes.
pgrep -af 'emulator_main|gateway_main|bigquery-emulator' \
  | grep -vE 'grep|/usr/bin/zsh' \
  | awk '{print $1}' \
  | xargs -r kill -TERM
sleep 1
pgrep -af 'emulator_main|gateway_main|bigquery-emulator' \
  | grep -vE 'grep|/usr/bin/zsh' \
  | awk '{print $1}' \
  | xargs -r kill -KILL
pgrep -af 'emulator_main|gateway_main|bigquery-emulator' \
  | grep -vE 'grep|/usr/bin/zsh' \
  || echo '(emulator/gateway clean)'

# 3. Conformance runner binaries (the Go test binary keeps them as children).
pgrep -af 'conformance/cmd/runner|/runner ' \
  | grep -vE 'grep|/usr/bin/zsh' \
  | awk '{print $1}' \
  | xargs -r kill -TERM
pgrep -af 'conformance/cmd/runner|/runner ' \
  | grep -vE 'grep|/usr/bin/zsh' \
  || echo '(runner clean)'

# 4. Docker — only when a docker build / compose was run this turn.
docker compose down -v --remove-orphans 2>/dev/null || true
docker ps -a --filter 'label=org.opencontainers.image.title=bigquery-emulator' --format '{{.ID}}' \
  | xargs -r docker rm -f >/dev/null 2>&1 || true
```

The first run of any of those `xargs` invocations is a no-op when there is nothing to kill — that's fine. The point is the audit; never skip the cleanup block "because there's probably nothing there".

## Reclaim memory (when `free -h` shows < 4 GiB available)

```bash
# BuildKit cache is the single biggest reclaimable bucket after an
# interrupted docker build. A failed `engine-builder` stage routinely
# leaves 5-15 GiB of reclaimable cache mount data. Always reclaim
# AGED entries first (do not blow the whole cache; warm rebuilds rely
# on it).
docker buildx du --verbose 2>/dev/null | tail -5
docker buildx prune --filter unused-for=1h --force

# Inactive containers + dangling images from interrupted iterations.
docker container prune --filter 'until=1h' --force
docker image prune --filter 'until=24h' --force

# Bazel disk cache on the host (the project's bazel server's external
# repo cache, NOT the in-container cache). Only nuke if disk pressure;
# warm host rebuilds rely on it.
# du -sh ~/.cache/bazel
```

After reclaiming, re-run the pre-spawn audit.

## Docker-specific guidance (the recent OOM source)

`docker build` for this repo runs Bazel **inside** the `engine-builder` stage. The Bazel inside that container auto-detects `nproc` and `MemTotal` from the host's perspective (Docker default mode). It therefore forks `nproc - 2` parallel `clang++` processes (~14 on this box), each potentially 2-4 GiB, while the host shell, Cursor (~2 GiB), Chrome, and any other host-side Bazel session are competing for the same RAM.

**When you `docker build` this repo locally, ALWAYS cap container-side Bazel:**

```bash
docker build \
  --build-arg BAZEL_JOBS=$(($(nproc) - 6)) \
  --build-arg BAZEL_MEM_MB=$(awk '/^MemTotal:/ { printf "%d\n", $2 / 2 / 1024 }' /proc/meminfo) \
  -t bigquery-emulator:local .
```

That leaves ~6 cores and ~half the host RAM for Cursor, Chrome, the IDE language servers, and the host's existing processes. CI runners (smaller boxes) can fall back to the Dockerfile's auto-detect since they have no other workload.

`task docker:build` and `task docker:smoke` may already forward these build-args; if not, **pass them explicitly** when iterating on the Dockerfile locally.

Do not run `docker build` while a host-side `bazel build` is also running for this repo. They will race for memory and one (or both) will OOM-kill.

## Subagent boundary

The parent agent owns cleanup, regardless of what the subagent did. After a subagent returns (success, failure, interrupt, OOM-kill):

1. Read the subagent's last-reported terminal state (don't trust "I cleaned up").
2. Run the full **Cleanup** block above (Bazel, emulator, runner, docker).
3. Run the full **Pre-spawn audit** + `free -h` before spawning the next subagent.
4. If any of the catalog patterns is still alive after a `kill -KILL`, escalate to the user — do not chain another subagent on top.

## Why this rule exists

A literal OOM happened during plan 43 (docker-compose-smoke): the subagent kicked off `docker build`, the in-container Bazel forked 14 clangs against the same RAM the host's Cursor + Chrome were using, and Linux's OOM killer reaped processes until the assistant session itself died. Post-mortem showed (a) 13.4 GiB of reclaimable BuildKit cache that had never been pruned, (b) no `--build-arg BAZEL_*` overrides on the `docker build`, and (c) no mid-loop poll to catch the runaway. This rule's three checkpoints (pre-spawn audit, mid-loop poll, cleanup block) all three would have prevented it.
